  urldate = {2023-07-10},
  abstract = {Researchers are increasingly using 24 h accelerometer wear protocols. No automated method has been published that accurately distinguishes `waking' wear time from other data (`in-bed', non-wear, invalid days) in young adults. This study examined the validity of an automated algorithm developed to achieve this for hip-worn Actigraph GT3X + 60 s epoch data. We compared the algorithm against a referent method (`into-bed' and `out-of-bed' times visually identified by two independent raters) and benchmarked against two published algorithms. All methods used the same non-wear rules. The development sample (n = 11) and validation sample (n = 95) were Australian young adults from the Raine pregnancy cohort (54\% female), all aged approximately 22 years. The agreement with Rater 1 in each minute's classification (yes/no) of waking wear time was examined as kappa ({$\kappa$}), limited to valid days ({$\geqslant$}10 h waking wear time per day) according to the algorithm and Rater 1. Bland\textendash Altman methods assessed agreement in daily totals of waking wear and in-bed wear time. Excellent agreement ({$\kappa$} {$>$} 0.75) was obtained between the raters for 80\% of participants (median {$\kappa$} = 0.94). The algorithm showed excellent agreement with Rater 1 ({$\kappa$} {$>$} 0.75) for 89\% of participants and poor agreement ({$\kappa$} {$<$} 0.40) for 1\%. In this sample, the algorithm (median {$\kappa$} = 0.86) performed better than algorithms validated in children (median {$\kappa$} = 0.77) and adolescents (median {$\kappa$} = 0.66). The mean difference (95\% limits of agreement) between Rater 1 and the algorithm was 7 (-220, 234) min d-1 for waking wear time on valid days and -41 (-309, 228) min d-1 for in-bed wear time. In this population, the automated algorithm's validity for identifying waking wear time was mostly good, not worse than inter-rater agreement, and better than the evaluated published alternatives. However, the algorithm requires improvement to better identify in-bed wear time.},
